The not guilty by reason of insanity plea is widely seen as Holmes' best - and perhaps his only - hope of avoiding the death penalty.

But his lawyers have held off until now, fearing a wrinkle in the law could cripple their ability to raise his mental health as a mitigating factor during the sentencing phase.

Two judges have refused to rule on the constitutionality of the law, saying the attorneys' objections were hypothetical because Holmes had not pleaded insanity.

The defense had little choice but to have Holmes enter the plea and then challenge the law.

Holmes' lawyers announced last week that he would ask to change his plea at Monday's hearing.

